Note:
ASN - Autonomous System Number (Tier 1)

Implements the ASN value type per RFC 1930 (Guidelines for creation,
selection, and registration of an Autonomous System) extended for 32-bit
ASNs by RFC 4893 (BGP Support for Four-octet Autonomous System Number
Space) and RFC 6793 (BGP Support for Four-Octet AS Number).

Representation:
  A 32-bit unsigned integer 0..4294967295.

Special-value classification per RFC 7607 (Codification of AS 0 Processing)
and RFC 5398 (Autonomous System (AS) Number Reservation for Documentation
Use):
  - AS 0                : reserved (RFC 7607)
  - AS 23456            : AS_TRANS placeholder for non-4-byte capable peers
                          (RFC 6793 section 9)
  - AS 64496..64511     : documentation 16-bit (RFC 5398)
  - AS 64512..65534     : private use 16-bit (RFC 6996)
  - AS 65535            : reserved (RFC 7300)
  - AS 65536..65551     : documentation 32-bit (RFC 5398)
  - AS 4200000000..4294967294 : private use 32-bit (RFC 6996)
  - AS 4294967295       : reserved (RFC 7300)

Text formatting:
  Canonical RFC 5396 "asplain" representation: "AS" prefix followed by
  decimal number (e.g. "AS65000", "AS4200000000"). This module emits the
  asplain form. The legacy "asdot" notation (e.g. "AS1.2") is not used
  for output; it is recognized only when parsing for forward compatibility.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/string_builder.runa" as SB
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/char_core.runa" as Char

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let ASN_MIN be 0
Let ASN_MAX be 4294967295
Let ASN_TRANS be 23456
Let ASN_RESERVED_HIGH be 4294967295
Let ASN_RESERVED_16BIT_HIGH be 65535
Let ASN_DOC_16BIT_MIN be 64496
Let ASN_DOC_16BIT_MAX be 64511
Let ASN_PRIVATE_16BIT_MIN be 64512
Let ASN_PRIVATE_16BIT_MAX be 65534
Let ASN_DOC_32BIT_MIN be 65536
Let ASN_DOC_32BIT_MAX be 65551
Let ASN_PRIVATE_32BIT_MIN be 4200000000
Let ASN_PRIVATE_32BIT_MAX be 4294967294

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Build an ASN from a raw 32-bit value. Validates against the full RFC 4893
range so callers cannot accidentally promote a 64-bit value into the ASN
space.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Range check 0..2^32 - 1. Identity assignment.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Out-of-range inputs return -1; callers must treat that as error.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_from_u32" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is less than ASN_MIN:
        Return -1
    End If
    If value is greater than ASN_MAX:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning
Format an ASN as RFC 5396 asplain "AS<decimal>". Result is a freshly
allocated null-terminated string owned by the caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Append literal 'A','S' then the integer-to-string conversion of the value.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) over the decimal length, n <= 10. Space: O(n) for the output.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No untrusted input handled. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_to_string" takes asn as Integer returns Integer:
    If asn is less than ASN_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If asn is greater than ASN_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If sb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 65
    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 83
    proc stringbuilder_append_integer from SB with sb, asn
    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with sb
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Parse "AS<decimal>" per RFC 5396 asplain. Case-insensitive on the "AS"
prefix. Returns -1 on malformed input.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Validate length >= 3. Verify first two characters are 'A' and 'S' (or
their lowercase equivalents). Parse the remaining bytes as a decimal
integer, accumulating into a 64-bit value with overflow check against
ASN_MAX.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n) over input length. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict validation: rejects leading whitespace, embedded non-digit
characters, and values exceeding 2^32 - 1.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_from_string" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    If length is less than 3:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let c0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, 0
    Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, 1
    Let is_a be 0
    If c0 is equal to 65:
        Set is_a to 1
    End If
    If c0 is equal to 97:
        Set is_a to 1
    End If
    Let is_s be 0
    If c1 is equal to 83:
        Set is_s to 1
    End If
    If c1 is equal to 115:
        Set is_s to 1
    End If
    If is_a is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If is_s is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let value be 0
    Let i be 2
    Let parse_failed be 0
    While i is less than length:
        If parse_failed is equal to 0:
            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, i
            Let is_d be proc is_digit from Char with ch
            If is_d is equal to 0:
                Set parse_failed to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set value to value multiplied by 10
                Set value to value plus (ch minus 48)
                If value is greater than ASN_MAX:
                    Set parse_failed to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If parse_failed is equal to 1:
        Return -1
    End If
    If i is less than 3:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
AS 0 is reserved per RFC 7607. Routes carrying AS 0 in the AS_PATH must
be discarded.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Equality with 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
BGP implementations drop AS 0 paths.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_is_reserved_zero" takes asn as Integer returns Integer:
    If asn is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Documentation ASNs (RFC 5398): 64496..64511 (16-bit) and 65536..65551
(32-bit). Used in examples; must not be allocated to real networks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Disjunction over the two documentation ranges.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Validation tools should reject documentation ASNs in production config.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_is_documentation" takes asn as Integer returns Integer:
    If asn is less than ASN_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If asn is greater than ASN_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If asn is greater than or equal to ASN_DOC_16BIT_MIN:
        If asn is less than or equal to ASN_DOC_16BIT_MAX:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If asn is greater than or equal to ASN_DOC_32BIT_MIN:
        If asn is less than or equal to ASN_DOC_32BIT_MAX:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Private-use ASNs (RFC 6996): 64512..65534 (16-bit) and 4200000000..
4294967294 (32-bit). Used for internal routing only; must not be exported
to the public Internet.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Disjunction over the two private-use ranges.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
BGP egress filters should strip private ASNs.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_is_private" takes asn as Integer returns Integer:
    If asn is less than ASN_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If asn is greater than ASN_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    If asn is greater than or equal to ASN_PRIVATE_16BIT_MIN:
        If asn is less than or equal to ASN_PRIVATE_16BIT_MAX:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If asn is greater than or equal to ASN_PRIVATE_32BIT_MIN:
        If asn is less than or equal to ASN_PRIVATE_32BIT_MAX:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
AS_TRANS (23456) is the placeholder used by RFC 4893 / RFC 6793 to
represent 32-bit ASNs to legacy 16-bit-only BGP peers. Should never
appear as a real autonomous system in production configuration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Equality with 23456.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Operators flag the presence of AS_TRANS as a sign of legacy interop.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_is_as_trans" takes asn as Integer returns Integer:
    If asn is equal to ASN_TRANS:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Test whether an ASN fits in the original 16-bit space (0..65535).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Upper bound check.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Used to dispatch between two-byte and four-byte AS_PATH encoding.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "asn_is_16bit" takes asn as Integer returns Integer:
    If asn is less than ASN_MIN:
        Return 0
    End If
    If asn is greater than ASN_RESERVED_16BIT_HIGH:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process
